00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.355
- Good morning, I am Liz Cohen.

00:00:12.355 --> 00:00:15.250
I'm dean of the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study,

00:00:15.250 --> 00:00:21.680
and I am delighted to welcome
you to Radcliffe Day 2018.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:26.630
Radcliffe Day is always exciting
and a highlight of the year.

00:00:26.630 --> 00:00:29.590
But it is especially
so for me this year.

00:00:29.590 --> 00:00:32.110
I will be stepping
down at the end of June

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:34.300
to return to the
History Department

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:37.690
after seven wonderful years
as dean of the Radcliffe

00:00:37.690 --> 00:00:39.264
Institute.

00:00:39.264 --> 00:00:39.805
Recognizing--

00:00:39.805 --> 00:00:42.725
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:58.928 --> 00:01:01.410
OK.

00:01:01.410 --> 00:01:03.350
Thank you very much.

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:07.080
Recognizing inspiring leaders
with a Radcliffe medal

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:11.460
has been one of the very
best parts of my job.

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:16.341
Today we honor a remarkable
public servant, Hillary Rodham

00:01:16.341 --> 00:01:16.840
Clinton.

00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:19.828
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:27.440
And I am pleased to have
such a fantastic crowd

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:29.660
joining me to do that.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:34.040
There are nearly 2,000 of us
here today in two tents, one

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:36.260
in Radcliffe Yard, the
other across the street

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:42.380
in Greenleaf Yard, making this
our largest Radcliffe Day ever.

00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:44.780
Many others are
watching online, and I'd

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:48.800
like to extend a
special welcome to them.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:51.230
This afternoon
starting at 12:30,

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:54.500
we will celebrate Secretary
Clinton's achievements

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:57.410
and award her the
Radcliffe Medal.

00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:01.400
Former Secretary of State
and 2001 Radcliffe medalist

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:05.090
Madeleine Albright will
offer a personal tribute.

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:08.300
And Secretary Clinton will
then engage in conversation

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.660
with our own Maura Healey,
a graduate of the Harvard

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:13.830
Radcliffe Class of 1992.

00:02:13.830 --> 00:02:16.782
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:25.080
And for those of you not from
Massachusetts, our attorney

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:27.090
general.

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:30.870
But first it is our
tradition to kick off

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:35.190
Radcliffe Day with a panel
discussion on a topic close

00:02:35.190 --> 00:02:38.520
to our honoree's head and heart.

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:40.890
This morning's
theme in recognition

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:44.370
of Hillary Clinton's service
as US Secretary of State

00:02:44.370 --> 00:02:50.400
from 2009 to 2013 is
America's role in the world.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:56.340
What has it been, what is it
now, and what should it be?

00:02:56.340 --> 00:03:00.300
We titled our panel Toward
a New Global Architecture

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:04.260
to recall major policy
speeches that Secretary Clinton

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:08.910
delivered in 2009 and
2010 at the Council

00:03:08.910 --> 00:03:10.920
on Foreign Relations.

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:14.850
In those speeches, Clinton
enumerated important challenges

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:18.210
that face the United
States, including conflicts

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:21.150
in the Middle East,
violent extremism,

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:25.320
nuclear proliferation,
climate change, and disease.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:28.710
And she called for a
new global architecture

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:31.440
that would enable
solutions to those issues

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:35.670
through collective action on
a global scale with the United

00:03:35.670 --> 00:03:39.450
States taking a bold
leadership role.

00:03:39.450 --> 00:03:42.840
These challenges demanded
an architecture in which,

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:46.500
and I quote her, "States
have clear incentives

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:50.250
to cooperate and live up
to their responsibilities

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:54.870
as well as strong disincentives
to sit on the sidelines

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:58.290
or sow discord and
division," end quote.

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.300
In constructing this
new architecture,

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:02.880
Clinton argued,
"the United States

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:08.130
can, must, and will lead in
this new century," end quote.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:10.620
Resharpening its
tools to undertake

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.800
what she called a smart
power approach that

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:16.860
transcends simplistic
distinctions

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:19.380
between hard and soft power.

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:23.100
Instead, the US should
implement a nimble statecraft

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:27.120
that strategically combines
goals like economic development

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:31.670
with, in her words, "good
old-fashioned diplomacy."

00:04:31.670 --> 00:04:33.840
The challenges Secretary
Clinton grappled

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:39.090
with almost 10 years ago
are still very much with us.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:43.500
And many of them feel
only more urgent today.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:46.630
All of them require
global solutions

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:49.980
in a world that is more
interconnected than ever

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:51.210
before.

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:53.640
As a result of our
interdependence,

00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:57.570
even challenges that once
seem solidly domestic

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:01.380
have become increasingly
global in nature.

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:04.630
Diseases don't respect
national borders.

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:09.480
We have seen this in the cases
of H1N1, SARS, MIRS, Zika,

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:14.010
and the 2013 to
2016 Ebola epidemic.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:17.310
Climate change has been a
global issue since we first

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:19.240
started talking about it.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:22.470
We know that we share
a single atmosphere,

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:25.530
but global cooperation
to reduce emissions

00:05:25.530 --> 00:05:28.200
continues to prove challenging.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.230
The threat posed by
non-state violent extremist

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:35.520
groups such as ISIS, Boko
Haram, the Taliban, al-Qaeda,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:40.320
and al-shabaab similarly
transcends political frontiers

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.140
and demands global cooperation.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.080
So, too, does the
massive displacement

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:50.250
of millions of people who
are refugees from conflicts

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:56.280
in Syria, South Sudan, Somalia,
Afghanistan, and elsewhere.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:06:00.420
In the face of these and many
other new and still evolving

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:04.140
global challenges, it
is imperative to return

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:09.000
to Secretary Clinton's question
and probe the current state

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.550
of the global
architecture and the role

00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:15.060
the United States is
playing in it hopefully

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.550
as a force for
peaceful stability,

00:06:17.550 --> 00:06:21.210
for moral leadership, and
human including women's rights,

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:23.520
for greater
worldwide prosperity,

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:27.390
and for solving
formidable world problems.

00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:29.940
In seeking solutions
moreover, we

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:34.290
must also avoid a growing
danger that Madeleine Albright

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:38.790
recently warned about, the
rising tide of authoritarianism

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:43.680
around the world from Russia to
the Philippines to Venezuela.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:46.380
As Albright wrote
last month, we may

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.920
be encouraged that most
people in most countries

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:52.770
still want to live
freely and in peace,

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.290
but there is no
ignoring the storm

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:57.540
clouds that have gathered.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:02.160
And she continued, "If one were
to draft a script chronicling

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:05.400
fascism's resurrection,
the abdication

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:08.130
of America's moral
leadership would

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:12.480
make a credible first
scene," end quote.

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:15.630
Recently, it seems
that the United States

00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:19.440
is lurching from one
crisis to another

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:22.460
whether it's the war in
Syria, the nuclear standoffs

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:24.890
with North Korea
and Iran, or the US

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:27.770
exit from international
agreements like the Paris

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:31.550
Climate Change Accord
and trade alliances.

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:36.560
The president has called for an
America First foreign policy,

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:42.920
but it bears asking what America
first means in today's world.

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:46.790
Over a century since Woodrow
Wilson used the slogan

00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:51.800
in his 1916 re-election
campaign to assuage fears

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:56.300
of US involvement in World
War I and so many decades

00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:58.430
since the America
First committee

00:07:58.430 --> 00:08:03.980
promoted its opposition to the
US's entry into World War II.

00:08:03.980 --> 00:08:06.920
In today's environment
of global challenges,

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:10.940
massive international
trade, population mobility,

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:14.660
technological transfer,
and high-tech threats,

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:18.170
can United States
really go it alone?

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:21.950
And if and when it does,
what does America First

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:27.740
convey to the rest of the
world, friends and foes alike.

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:31.970
Our panel this morning provides
an exceptional opportunity

00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:35.659
to step back and begin
to piece together

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:39.289
the current state of the global
architecture and the role

00:08:39.289 --> 00:08:42.980
that the United States
is assuming within it.

00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:47.690
What do recent American actions
and reactions add up to?

00:08:47.690 --> 00:08:49.640
Where are we headed?

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:52.760
What kind of
expertise is needed?

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:57.050
And how should we as
individuals and as a country

00:08:57.050 --> 00:09:00.860
think about America's
role and responsibilities

00:09:00.860 --> 00:09:04.910
in this seemingly ever
more precarious world?

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:08.310
We could have no better guide
to this important discussion

00:09:08.310 --> 00:09:11.930
than Nicholas Burns, who is the
Roy and Barbara Goodman Family

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:14.090
Professor of the
practice of diplomacy

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:17.780
and international relations
at the Harvard Kennedy School

00:09:17.780 --> 00:09:21.200
where he also leads the
future of diplomacy project

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:25.580
and the project on Europe and
the Transatlantic relationship.

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:29.420
Nicks Burns is director of
the Aspen Strategy Group,

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:33.460
and he sits on too many boards
and advisory groups to name.

00:09:33.460 --> 00:09:36.310
But before joining
the Kennedy School,

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:40.650
Burns was a member of the US
Foreign Service for 27 years,

00:09:40.650 --> 00:09:43.760
including as US
ambassador to Greece,

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:50.180
US ambassador to NATO, and from
2005 to 2008 as undersecretary

00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:53.750
of state for Political Affairs
where he led negotiations

00:09:53.750 --> 00:09:56.270
on the US India civil
nuclear agreement,

00:09:56.270 --> 00:09:59.630
Iran's nuclear
program, and much more.

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:03.710
I am enormously grateful to Nick
for taking on this assignment

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:08.270
today and for all the help he
has given me over the past year

00:10:08.270 --> 00:10:11.000
as we plan together for today.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.040
He will introduce our
panelists and then he

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:15.980
will engage them in
discussion, so please join me

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:18.290
in warmly welcoming
Nicholas Burns.

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:21.194
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:29.906 --> 00:10:31.110
- Liz, thank you.

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:33.900
Good morning, everybody
on this beautiful morning

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:35.460
in Radcliffe Yard.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.160
We have a lot of people to
thank for this tremendous day.

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:42.330
But there is one woman who
has led this Institute,

00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:44.336
and she's walking
right in front of me.

00:10:44.336 --> 00:10:47.192
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:52.910 --> 00:10:58.850
She has led it with strength
and dynamism and passion

00:10:58.850 --> 00:11:03.410
and an unfailing belief that
reason and empirical thought

00:11:03.410 --> 00:11:06.545
and the pursuit of knowledge
represent the highest values

00:11:06.545 --> 00:11:09.980
of Radcliffe Institute and
of Harvard University .

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.860
She has expanded
Radcliffe's public programs.

00:11:13.860 --> 00:11:16.670
She has added new
professorships.

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:20.210
If you take a look around
this glorious Radcliffe Yard,

00:11:20.210 --> 00:11:23.630
she's brought art
and art installations

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:25.070
into the heart of the yard.

00:11:25.070 --> 00:11:28.840
And she's embraced our president
Drew Faust vision of one

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:31.100
Harvard may it ever be so.

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:33.470
I think after seven
extraordinary years,

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:37.151
she deserves another
rousing round of applause.

00:11:37.151 --> 00:11:40.073
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:51.580
It is a privilege for
all of us to be here

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:56.170
with the most extraordinary,
most accomplished public

00:11:56.170 --> 00:12:00.790
servant that we have had in this
country in a long, long time,

00:12:00.790 --> 00:12:02.660
Hillary Rodham Clinton.

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:05.522
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:13.170 --> 00:12:19.500
As an attorney from another
law school, as a civic leader,

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:21.810
as an advocate for
children for the poor

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:26.730
and for women, as First Lady,
as United States senator,

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:29.460
as our secretary
of state, she has

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:33.930
served with exemplary
determination and intelligence

00:12:33.930 --> 00:12:36.750
and resilience and courage.

00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:39.120
And as we begin our
discussion today

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:40.710
of a very complex subject--

00:12:40.710 --> 00:12:44.100
what is America's relationship
to the rest of the world, what

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:47.090
is America trying to
achieve in that world--

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:49.740
we will have Secretary
Clinton's prodigious record

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:52.530
of accomplishment
to help guide us.

00:12:52.530 --> 00:12:56.910
From her first national speech
on a stage 10 miles west

00:12:56.910 --> 00:13:03.780
of here at Wellesley
College in 1969

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:07.680
to her pathbreaking
exhortation in Beijing

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:11.400
at a seminal conference in
1995 that human rights are

00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:15.807
women's rights and women's
rights are human rights--

00:13:15.807 --> 00:13:18.729
[APPLAUSE]

00:13:22.150 --> 00:13:26.170
To her untiring support for
the United States military

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:29.140
when she was a senator
from the state of New York

00:13:29.140 --> 00:13:32.020
to her four a
challenging consequential

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:34.900
and often, I'm sure,
exhausting years

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:37.540
as our 67th secretary
of state, she

00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:42.670
has given with every ounce
of persistence and hope

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:46.660
and determination, she
showed us how America can

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:49.920
be great on the world stage.

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:51.940
And I think she may
exemplify better than just

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:56.260
about anybody I know Theodore
Roosevelt's belief that it's

00:13:56.260 --> 00:14:00.070
not the critic who counts,
that the credit belongs,

00:14:00.070 --> 00:14:05.030
in this case, to the woman
who is in the arena, who

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:09.250
is in the public square, who
is in the middle of the action,

00:14:09.250 --> 00:14:12.710
and, in Roosevelt's words, who
knows the great enthusiasms,

00:14:12.710 --> 00:14:17.440
the great devotions, who spends
herself in a worthy cause

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:21.490
so, as TR said so memorably,
her place shall never

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:26.530
be with those cold and timid
souls who know neither victory

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:28.180
nor defeat.

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:31.840
She has been in the
arena for all of us

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:35.290
for the United States for
her entire adult life.

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:38.170
As secretary of state, she
steered America's response

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:40.480
to the Arab revolutions.

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:45.730
She stood up to the Chinese in
2010 on the South China Sea.

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:50.260
She stood up to a
truculent Vladimir Putin

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:51.840
in Eastern Europe.

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:52.400
She ended--

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:54.590
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:54.590 --> 00:14:58.270
And read her memoirs and
you'll get the detail on that.

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:00.700
She ended a bitter
and bloody rocket war

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:03.400
between Israel and Hezbollah.

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:05.620
And she managed
nuclear arms reductions

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:07.630
to make this a safer world.

00:15:07.630 --> 00:15:11.530
She also-- and Anne-Marie will
talk about this I'm sure today

00:15:11.530 --> 00:15:13.780
because Anne-Marie
was a big part of it--

00:15:13.780 --> 00:15:16.330
she pioneered an important
conceptual change

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:18.435
about how we should
think about diplomacy.

00:15:18.435 --> 00:15:21.790
It was her insight that
American diplomacy,

00:15:21.790 --> 00:15:24.850
American development,
and American defense

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:29.860
must all be linked in one
cohesive national strategy.

00:15:29.860 --> 00:15:35.020
And in contrast to the
absolutely deplorable lack

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:39.580
of support for our diplomats
over the last year,

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:42.790
she inspired our diplomats
to represent the United

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:45.280
States, our young
women, our young men,

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:47.210
all around the world.

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:50.080
So this panel's meeting
at an important moment

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:53.500
where America's greatness
on the global stage

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:57.640
is being challenged as never
before, what has made America

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:01.150
an exceptional nation,
the indispensable nation

00:16:01.150 --> 00:16:04.090
as President Clinton and
Secretary Albright used

00:16:04.090 --> 00:16:09.400
to remind us, what has made us
the undisputed global nation,

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:14.530
a great nation since the Second
World War to 9/11 and the years

00:16:14.530 --> 00:16:15.850
since?

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:18.940
We had to be an
outward looking people.

00:16:18.940 --> 00:16:21.340
We had to understand
that we had to be

00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:23.680
part of the global
comments, engage

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:25.690
with the rest of the
world, not digging

00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:28.000
a moat around the
country and pulling up

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.570
the drawbridge bridges but
actually being in the world

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:33.580
as a leader.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:36.430
Our closest friends
and our allies

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:42.030
lament the fact that we are
very far from that vision now.

00:16:42.030 --> 00:16:45.160
And it's important to remember
a little bit of history.

00:16:45.160 --> 00:16:48.130
After World War II,
every president--

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:51.520
until President Trump--
every president, Republican

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:55.120
and Democrat, believed that
our power and purpose was based

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:58.000
on enduring foundations,
our alliances

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.180
like NATO, free
trade, a willingness

00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:05.950
to keep America's doors open
to immigration and refugees,

00:17:05.950 --> 00:17:08.230
a willingness to lead in
the defense of human rights

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:11.349
and of democracy and
of democratic ideals

00:17:11.349 --> 00:17:13.359
when they're
challenged as Madeleine

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:16.240
has written about
in her new book.

00:17:16.240 --> 00:17:19.150
But the cruel reality is this.

00:17:19.150 --> 00:17:23.770
We are now retreating
in all of those areas.

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:29.650
Our government has abandoned the
Paris Climate Change Accords,

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:33.490
abandoned three major
trade agreements,

00:17:33.490 --> 00:17:40.180
abandoned the Iran nuclear deal,
abandoned our historic position

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:44.320
on Jerusalem, and may now
be abandoning the pursuit

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:47.680
of diplomacy in North Korea.

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:51.190
We're no longer leading in
the tradition of Marshall

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:56.150
and Acheson, of Dulles and
Herter, of James A. Baker,

00:17:56.150 --> 00:18:00.610
of Madeleine Albright, of Colin
Powell, of Condoleezza Rice,

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:04.030
and Hillary Rodham Clinton.

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.840
Winston Churchill visited
Harvard and Radcliffe

00:18:07.840 --> 00:18:12.490
in September 1943, and he
addressed the students here

00:18:12.490 --> 00:18:14.100
at this university.

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:18.160
And it was an epochal
time in a terrible war.

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:21.950
It was just after the Allied
victories at Stalingrad and El

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:25.070
Alamein just after
the commencement

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:27.140
of the Italian campaign.

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:30.470
The US was taking the
metaphorical baton

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:35.810
of leadership from Britain as
the world's strongest power.

00:18:35.810 --> 00:18:37.790
And at that critical
moment when so much rested

00:18:37.790 --> 00:18:41.030
on our shoulders,
here's what Churchill

00:18:41.030 --> 00:18:45.350
said to the students of
Harvard and Radcliffe.

00:18:45.350 --> 00:18:50.750
He said, "The price of
greatness is responsibility."

00:18:50.750 --> 00:18:53.660
The price of greatness
responsibility.

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:57.770
To be truly great in our
time, the United States

00:18:57.770 --> 00:19:01.130
needs to lead with
strategic purpose,

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:05.870
with respect for other
countries and other peoples,

00:19:05.870 --> 00:19:08.720
with dignity, with
dedication to help

00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:12.350
advance justice and democracy
and peace in the world.

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:15.890
And we have strayed so
far from that mission

00:19:15.890 --> 00:19:21.200
under Donald Trump's chaotic,
weak, and fearful leadership

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:23.260
of our country.

00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:28.210
But in her life and
work, Hillary Clinton

00:19:28.210 --> 00:19:31.390
has been all about
responsibility.

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:33.700
We're fortunate to
have the example

00:19:33.700 --> 00:19:37.750
of that responsible leadership
today to help guide us

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:41.890
and to renew America's
greatness as we move forward.

00:19:41.890 --> 00:19:43.870
Such an honor to be here.

00:19:43.870 --> 00:19:47.170
And we have four very
distinguished panelists.

00:19:47.170 --> 00:19:51.400
Starting at the far end
of the table on my left,

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:53.500
Anne-Marie Slaughter,
former Director of Policy

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:57.850
Planning at the State Department
for Secretary Clinton,

00:19:57.850 --> 00:20:01.480
a graduate of Harvard Law
School, now president and CEO

00:20:01.480 --> 00:20:04.300
of the New America Foundation.

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:08.770
Meghan O'Sullivan, former
Deputy National Security Adviser

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:13.120
to President George W. Bush
for Iraq and Afghanistan.

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:16.360
How's that for a
tough challenge.

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:19.090
Now the Jeane Kirkpatrick
Professor of the Practice

00:20:19.090 --> 00:20:21.670
of international
affairs and my colleague

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:24.070
at the Harvard Kennedy School.

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:28.540
David Ignatius,
Washington Post columnist,

00:20:28.540 --> 00:20:33.190
foreign policy thought
leader, spy novelist--

00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:36.130
read The Quantum
Spy, his latest--

00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:39.760
a graduate of Harvard College.

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:43.270
And Michele Flournoy,
former undersecretary

00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:47.440
of defense for policy, a
graduate of Harvard College

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:51.880
back in a reunion year,
now managing director

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:53.689
of west exec advisors.

00:20:53.689 --> 00:20:54.855
Let's get to our discussion.

00:20:54.855 --> 00:20:55.980
Thank you.

