00:22:46.850 --> 00:22:49.480
So, Nick, to answer
your question,

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.280
we are not leading in the world.

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:57.610
But I want to frame my
answer in the context

00:22:57.610 --> 00:23:00.880
of a message the American
people have been sending us

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:03.490
and we in this room and
this great university

00:23:03.490 --> 00:23:06.040
and all the great
universities I've been part of

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:09.220
and Washington
are not listening.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:12.340
Ever since the end
of the Cold War,

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:15.430
the candidate that
said I don't want

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:17.860
to continue being
the global hegemon

00:23:17.860 --> 00:23:21.760
and spending our money
that way has won.

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:26.440
In 1992, President
George HW Bush,

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:29.920
the hero of ending the
Cold War, the most literate

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:34.730
foreign policy president we
had had in a very long time,

00:23:34.730 --> 00:23:38.350
lost to this governor
from the south

00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:41.770
who didn't really talk
about foreign policy a lot

00:23:41.770 --> 00:23:42.520
in his election.

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:46.460
He said, "It's the
economy, stupid."

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:49.180
And I as a governor
of Arkansas know

00:23:49.180 --> 00:23:51.700
what to do for this country.

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:56.890
In 2000, his vice president,
another southerner,

00:23:56.890 --> 00:24:00.890
who was an extraordinary
global diplomat--

00:24:00.890 --> 00:24:03.490
he had led the work with Russia.

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:06.190
He had been all over
the world, and he

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:09.430
ran against another southern
governor, who basically

00:24:09.430 --> 00:24:11.800
said I don't know
much about the world,

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:15.280
but we need a kinder,
gentler nation.

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:17.500
Guess who won?

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:19.970
In 2004, similar pattern.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:23.320
2008, John McCain ran.

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:28.210
I am not of John McCain's party,
but I have enormous respect

00:24:28.210 --> 00:24:29.380
for John McCain.

00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:32.760
John McCain has stood up for
the best of our traditions.

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:33.660
He stood up against--

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:36.498
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:39.820 --> 00:24:42.340
I will never forget
in the aughts

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:44.860
when I was here
teaching at the time--

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:47.920
when suddenly people were
actually talking about torture

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:49.840
was OK for our country.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:52.210
It was necessary, and
we're hearing that again.

00:24:52.210 --> 00:24:54.670
And John McCain led
that fight, and he

00:24:54.670 --> 00:24:58.060
had been obviously a
participant in the great--

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.130
in great global
events of our time.

00:25:00.130 --> 00:25:03.640
But against Barack Obama,
he was the globalist,

00:25:03.640 --> 00:25:05.750
and there was a
senator from Illinois

00:25:05.750 --> 00:25:07.930
who talked about bringing
this country together,

00:25:07.930 --> 00:25:10.750
who rejected the Iraq war.

00:25:10.750 --> 00:25:12.520
Guess who won.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:15.790
And I don't think I have to
tell you the story of 2016,

00:25:15.790 --> 00:25:23.770
but it is the most horrific
example of somebody saying

00:25:23.770 --> 00:25:24.610
it's--

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:28.690
I don't want this role in
the world and somebody else

00:25:28.690 --> 00:25:31.990
saying we must have
this role in the world,

00:25:31.990 --> 00:25:33.400
and we're not winning.

00:25:33.400 --> 00:25:36.370
So I just want to say
a couple of things

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:39.310
about how it is
time to stopped--

00:25:39.310 --> 00:25:43.390
to stop rejecting
that message or trying

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:48.680
to instruct those who send it on
how they really are misguided.

00:25:48.680 --> 00:25:52.600
It's time to listen
to that message.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:54.790
And in many ways
they're telling us

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:57.340
something Secretary
Clinton taught me

00:25:57.340 --> 00:25:59.590
because one of the things I
had the privilege of doing

00:25:59.590 --> 00:26:03.560
was working with her on her
first big development speech.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.170
And she said to us--

00:26:05.170 --> 00:26:08.890
she tasked a group of us
to think about what should

00:26:08.890 --> 00:26:11.200
American development policy be.

00:26:11.200 --> 00:26:14.860
And she said it
cannot be charity.

00:26:14.860 --> 00:26:18.380
I need to tell the
person in Detroit

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:22.060
why I am spending American
taxpayers' dollars

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:24.370
in Africa and not in Detroit.

00:26:24.370 --> 00:26:28.930
And I must have an account that
makes sense to that person.

00:26:28.930 --> 00:26:34.610
We need to think about how
we can lead in the world

00:26:34.610 --> 00:26:36.850
and in a different way.

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:41.260
And we-- to start, we have to
recognize that right now, we

00:26:41.260 --> 00:26:45.400
are less the global hegemon
than the global hypocrite.

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:49.300
We are preaching values of
democracy and universal values

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:51.400
we are not practicing at home.

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:54.610
We are preaching prosperity and
our country is falling apart.

00:26:54.610 --> 00:26:55.750
I live on Amtrak.

00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:57.190
I know of what I speak.

00:26:59.770 --> 00:27:04.060
But second, we need to make
foreign policy and diplomacy

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:06.550
the work of many,
many more people

00:27:06.550 --> 00:27:10.000
than those of us on this
panel and in this university

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.320
and in Washington.

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:16.620
LA appointed the
first deputy mayor

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:19.830
for International
Affairs that person--

00:27:19.830 --> 00:27:21.750
I'm proud to say
she's a woman-- is

00:27:21.750 --> 00:27:26.000
former ambassador in the Obama
administration Nina Hachigian,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.240
she's in Los Angeles
doing foreign affairs.

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:33.790
Chicago has 28 sister
city relationships.

00:27:33.790 --> 00:27:36.120
If you ever walk from
O'Hare to the Hilton, which

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:38.070
I've done many,
many, many times,

00:27:38.070 --> 00:27:40.170
it's a Hall of United Nations.

00:27:40.170 --> 00:27:44.010
28 nations flags
hang in that walkway.

00:27:44.010 --> 00:27:47.730
Cities across the country
are playing as important role

00:27:47.730 --> 00:27:51.330
in fighting terrorism
in climate change.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:53.850
President Trump pulled
out, but the cities

00:27:53.850 --> 00:27:56.730
of the United States, led by
Mayor Bloomberg, stood up.

00:27:56.730 --> 00:27:58.770
And we are going to
meet our commitments

00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:02.310
through those city's efforts
and the efforts of universities,

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:07.320
businesses, nonprofit leaders,
faith leaders, all of us.

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:10.660
So what I would say to come
back to Nick's questions--

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:14.940
just a slight digression--

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:18.720
we have to first of
all listen to Americans

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:23.220
who are saying when we were
under mortal threat in the Cold

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:25.990
War fighting the Soviet
Union nuclear weapon

00:28:25.990 --> 00:28:26.970
to nuclear weapon--

00:28:26.970 --> 00:28:29.700
and let us hope that day
doesn't come fully again.

00:28:29.700 --> 00:28:31.320
We're back to
fighting Russia but

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.180
in a different configuration.

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:35.970
In those days, we
would bear any price--

00:28:35.970 --> 00:28:38.100
pay any price and
bear any burden,

00:28:38.100 --> 00:28:42.360
but today we need to pay more
attention to what is happening

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:44.070
in the United States.

00:28:44.070 --> 00:28:48.300
So we need to learn how to
lead because I deeply believe--

00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:51.330
to paraphrase
Secretary Albright--

00:28:51.330 --> 00:28:54.510
we are an indispensable nation.

00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:56.520
We are not the only
one, but we are

00:28:56.520 --> 00:28:59.410
a nation that needs to
be at the global table.

00:28:59.410 --> 00:29:02.460
And when we are, the
world is a better place.

00:29:02.460 --> 00:29:06.960
But to get there, we have
to listen to Americans.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:10.110
We have to learn how to
lead in a different way

00:29:10.110 --> 00:29:15.030
and to not only have the great
diplomats like Nick Burns

00:29:15.030 --> 00:29:18.600
but to have all those people who
are not in the Foreign Service

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:21.570
but who are representing
America in the world

00:29:21.570 --> 00:29:25.810
be a part of who we are and
what we do in the world.

00:29:25.810 --> 00:29:26.310
Thank you.

00:29:26.310 --> 00:29:29.304
