others have stated--

00:30:57.030 --> 00:30:59.180
but I think it's very
important to note--

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:03.260
is that over the last 70 years,
the world has really prospered.

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:07.490
This has been a period of
unprecedented prosperity

00:31:07.490 --> 00:31:09.620
and peace on large
account because

00:31:09.620 --> 00:31:11.960
of the web of
institutions and norms

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:15.560
that have underpinned a lot of
what has gone on in the world,

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:18.680
and the US has just been
the most critical actor,

00:31:18.680 --> 00:31:23.060
not only in constructing that
web of institutions and norms

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:24.590
but in defending it.

00:31:24.590 --> 00:31:27.170
And I think any
president at this moment

00:31:27.170 --> 00:31:31.040
would have a challenge with this
order, with rejuvenating it,

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:33.300
with bringing it
up to the moment.

00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:36.210
The world is very different
than it was 70 years ago,

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:37.970
and I think any
president would have

00:31:37.970 --> 00:31:42.020
the challenge of modernizing
this international order as we

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:45.260
call it and dealing
with new challenges

00:31:45.260 --> 00:31:49.550
to that order be it China, be
it global disease, whatever

00:31:49.550 --> 00:31:50.930
the case may be.

00:31:50.930 --> 00:31:53.390
Unfortunately, we're not
having that conversation, which

00:31:53.390 --> 00:31:55.580
would be much wonkier
but much more welcome

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:58.370
and that would be how to reform
this international order.

00:31:58.370 --> 00:31:59.810
We're having a
conversation about

00:31:59.810 --> 00:32:01.730
are we still invested in it.

00:32:01.730 --> 00:32:05.540
And as others have
suggested, we really--

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:10.100
despite Anne-Marie's laying out
the electoral map over the last

00:32:10.100 --> 00:32:11.210
couple of decades--

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:13.910
we have the first
president in office

00:32:13.910 --> 00:32:16.220
who has questioned
openly whether it

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:18.320
is in America's
interest to continue

00:32:18.320 --> 00:32:21.930
to be the defender of this
particular role in the world.

00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:24.210
So others maybe
didn't campaign on it,

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:27.110
but once that person came
into the Oval Office,

00:32:27.110 --> 00:32:29.240
the imperative of American
leadership, I think,

00:32:29.240 --> 00:32:30.290
has always been clear.

00:32:30.290 --> 00:32:33.230
So we are at a unique
moment with a president who

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:36.350
does question whether
this as good for America.

00:32:36.350 --> 00:32:39.750
And this is concerning
because it takes leadership,

00:32:39.750 --> 00:32:42.620
particularly in a moment where
there are lots of anxieties

00:32:42.620 --> 00:32:44.060
about globalization.

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:46.730
It takes leadership not
only from the Oval Office

00:32:46.730 --> 00:32:49.340
but I would say most
importantly from the Oval Office

00:32:49.340 --> 00:32:52.370
to build and
maintain a consensus

00:32:52.370 --> 00:32:55.100
within our own country about
the importance of America

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:56.870
playing this role
and to make sure

00:32:56.870 --> 00:33:01.100
that consensus is not based
just on people on the stage

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:03.740
or people in this tent
but that it is one that

00:33:03.740 --> 00:33:06.010
embraces elites and non-elites.

00:33:06.010 --> 00:33:10.250
It embraces, as Anne-Maria
said, all parts of our country.

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:11.750
To get to your
question specifically

00:33:11.750 --> 00:33:14.480
about the Republican
Party, and here's

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:17.960
where I'm injecting
optimism, I would

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:20.360
say it is still
important to distinguish

00:33:20.360 --> 00:33:23.780
between the president
and the Republican Party.

00:33:23.780 --> 00:33:26.510
Many Republicans-- and I would
consider myself one of them--

00:33:26.510 --> 00:33:30.170
don't really see
him as a Republican.

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:32.660
And he has departed
from very traditional

00:33:32.660 --> 00:33:35.330
core Republican
values and policies

00:33:35.330 --> 00:33:37.610
in very, very fundamental ways.

00:33:37.610 --> 00:33:39.470
Now I think this is
a little disguised

00:33:39.470 --> 00:33:43.740
by the tax cuts because you have
seen the Republican leadership

00:33:43.740 --> 00:33:47.010
and really rallied behind
the president in this regard.

00:33:47.010 --> 00:33:51.080
But if we look at the menu
of policies and attitudes

00:33:51.080 --> 00:33:53.360
and orientations,
I still think there

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:56.780
is a pretty significant
gap between the president

00:33:56.780 --> 00:33:58.190
and the bulk of
the party when it

00:33:58.190 --> 00:34:00.316
comes to international affairs.

00:34:00.316 --> 00:34:01.690
I could go through
the long list,

00:34:01.690 --> 00:34:03.189
but in the interest
of time I won't.

00:34:03.189 --> 00:34:05.990
I'll simply say, take
trade for instance.

00:34:05.990 --> 00:34:08.270
The president's been
very vocal about trade.

00:34:08.270 --> 00:34:10.810
This is one of the things
that has been very consistent,

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:12.949
one of the few things that
has been very consistent

00:34:12.949 --> 00:34:15.090
in his policy agenda.

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:19.290
He is not someone who extols
the value of free trade.

00:34:19.290 --> 00:34:24.949
He openly embraced protectionism
in his inaugural speech.

00:34:24.949 --> 00:34:28.130
But I think there's still
a very strong support

00:34:28.130 --> 00:34:30.260
for free trade
among Republicans,

00:34:30.260 --> 00:34:32.760
among American business.

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:35.120
And I would say, if
you look at polls,

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:38.150
most Americans still are
more in favor of free trade

00:34:38.150 --> 00:34:39.750
than they are against it.

00:34:39.750 --> 00:34:42.630
And so I think there is
still a lot to work with.

00:34:42.630 --> 00:34:44.420
And that's true for
alliances as well.

00:34:44.420 --> 00:34:47.517
Americans like alliances,
Democrat, Republican.

00:34:47.517 --> 00:34:49.100
And just because the
president doesn't

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:51.980
seem to value them as much
as many of us would like

00:34:51.980 --> 00:34:56.659
doesn't mean that we no longer
have a national foundation

00:34:56.659 --> 00:34:57.930
for these things.

00:34:57.930 --> 00:35:01.100
So again I won't go through the
whole list of areas in which I

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:04.100
think we still have
a strong foundation

00:35:04.100 --> 00:35:06.500
and a strong national
interest, but I

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:10.220
do think we are at a moment of
a crisis of leadership, which

00:35:10.220 --> 00:35:13.100
is why it's such a
wonderful day to honor

00:35:13.100 --> 00:35:16.360
some national
leadership in this tent.

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:17.510
- Meghan, thank you.

